# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: authoritative-server
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] On online games, cheating subverts the rules or mechanics of the games to gain an unfair advantage over other players, generally with the use of third-party software.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] What constitutes cheating is dependent on the game involved, its rules, and consensus opinion as to whether a particular activity is considered to be cheating.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] Cheating is present in most multiplayer online games, but it is difficult to measure.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] Various methods of cheating in online games can take the form of software assistance, such as scripts and bots, and various forms of unsporting play taking advantage of exploits or glitches within the game.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] The Internet and darknets can provide players with the methodology necessary to cheat in online games, with software often available for purchase.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] As methods of cheating have advanced, video game publishers have similarly improved methods of anti-cheating, but are still limited in their effectiveness.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] Punishments for cheaters also have various forms, with legal measures also being taken against those who create or use cheats.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] While some countries include laws that prohibit and punish cheating, video game companies have a history of citing copyright infringement in lawsuits against cheaters.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] An aimbot or autoaim is a type of computer game bot most commonly used in first-person shooter games to provide varying levels of automated target acquisition and calibration to the player.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] They are sometimes used along with a triggerbot, which automatically shoots when an opponent appears within the field-of-view or aiming reticule of the player.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] Aimbotting relies on each player's client computer receiving information about all other players, whether they are visible from the player's position or not.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] Targeting is a matter of determining the location of any opponent relative to the player's location and pointing the player's weapon at the target.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] This targeting works regardless of whether the opponent is behind walls or too far away to be seen directly.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] Some servers allow inactive players to spectate, watching the game from the viewpoints of the active players.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] Recording of gameplay actions is also often possible.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] If someone was using a targeting aimbot, the bot would be obvious to the spectator as unnatural exact position tracking.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] Some aimbots and triggerbots attempt to hide from spectators the fact they are being used through a number of methods, such as delaying firing to hide the fact it shoots the instant an opponent is in the cheater's crosshair.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] Some triggerbot programs can be easily toggled on and off using the mouse or keyboard.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] Cheat suites may incorporate these in addition to other features, including adjustments to extrasensory perception, move speed, ammo count, and player radar.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] Neophytes may colloquially define these suites as aimbot programs.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] In the peer-to-peer gaming model, lagging is what happens when the stream of data between one or more players gets slowed or interrupted, causing movement to stutter and making opponents appear to behave erratically.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] By using a lag switch, a player is able to disrupt uploads from the client to the server, while their own client queues up the actions performed.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] The goal is to gain advantage over another player without reciprocation; opponents slow down or stop moving, allowing the lag switch user to easily outmaneuver them.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] From the opponent's perspective, the player using the device may appear to be teleporting, invisible or invincible, while the opponents suffer delayed animations and fast-forwarded game play, delivered in bursts.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] Some gaming communities refer to this method as "tapping" which refers to the users "tapping" on and off their internet connection to create the lag.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] The term "lag switch" encompasses many methods of disrupting the network communication between a client and its server.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] One method is by attaching a physical device, called a hardware lag switch, to a standard Ethernet cable.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] By flipping the switch on and off, the physical connection between the client and the server is disrupted.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] The designers of video game console hardware have started to introduce built-in protection against lag switches in the form of voltage detectors, which detect a change in voltage when the switch is flipped.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] Some manufacturers have taken counter measures to bypass or trick this detector.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] This can also be achieved by simply unplugging the Ethernet cord going to the client, causing a disruption in the player's internet connection.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] Other methods, called a software or wireless lag switch, involve using a computer program.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] In this method, the cheater runs an application on a computer connected to the same network as the client.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] The application hogs the network bandwidth, disrupting the communication between the client and its server.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] However, one cannot do this for an unlimited amount of time.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] At some point, if no traffic is being received, most game clients and/or game servers will decide that the connection has been lost and will remove the player from the game.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] In some P2P games, it can result in all players lagging or being disconnected from the game.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] Simpler methods are firewall or router rules that apply bandwidth shaping and network latency, a cheat is able to adjust limits on both bandwidth and latency to stay relevant to a P2P network yet have considerable advantage over other players.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] Look-ahead cheating is a method of cheating within a peer-to-peer multiplayer gaming architecture where the cheating client gains an unfair advantage by delaying their actions to see what other players do before announcing its own action.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] A partial solution is the lockstep protocol.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] A common aspect of real-time strategy games is the player's partial limitation or complete inability to see beyond the visibility range of individual game objects that are under their ownership (typically units and structures); this concept is controlled by a mechanism known as the fog of war.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] World-hacking usually enables the user to bypass this mechanism, either by removing it entirely and/or by rendering objects through the fog that would not normally be visible.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] In multiplayer modes, this allows for a distinct advantage against the other players who are subject to the intended settings.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] The advantage gained can be substantial, especially for the average real-time strategy games that rely on the rock paper scissors dynamic to balance out individual objects' varying strengths and weaknesses.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] World-hacking may also allow a player to see through solid or opaque objects and/or manipulate or remove textures, to know in advance when an opponent is about to come into targeting range from an occluded area.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] This can be done by making wall textures transparent, or modifying the game maps to insert polygonal holes into otherwise solid walls.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] This variation is commonly known as a "wallhack" since it basically allows to the player to see enemies through walls.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] World-hacking relies on the fact that an FPS server usually sends raw positional information for all players in the game, and leaves it up to the client's 3D renderer to hide opponents behind walls, in plant foliage, or in dark shadows.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] If the game map rendering could be turned off completely, all players could be seen moving around in what appears to be empty space.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] Complete map hiding offers no advantage to a cheater as they would be unable to navigate the invisible map pathways and obstacles.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] However, if only certain surfaces are made transparent or removed, this leaves just enough of an outline of the world to allow the cheater still to navigate it easily.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] In the context of mobile gaming, world-hacking has evolved to exploit the Unity engine's rendering pipeline.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] On platforms like Android, third-party software for *Standoff 2* utilizes shader modification (Chams) and library hooking to bypass occluded geometry, providing real-time visual advantages.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] Asus released wireframe display drivers in 2001 that enabled players to use wallhacks, announcing the settings as "special weapons" that users could employ in multiplayer games.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] In a poll by the Online Gamers Association, 90% of its members were against the release of the drivers.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] Players will set up multiple accounts to play against each other.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] Usually, the primary account will be allowed to win through a deliberate lack of resistance from the secondary account(s) due to those accounts being unplayed or those players agreeing to lose.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] Some players will reverse roles between games, giving each account an equal win–loss record.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] In games where wins and losses are recorded on a player's account, a player may disconnect when they are about to lose in order to prevent that loss from being recorded.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] This is usually done by activating known in-game glitches or through third-party sources via "IP booting" (a feature of firewall software).
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] Some players do this if they feel their opponent is being unfair.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] Some games implement a disconnection penalty, usually by recording the disconnect as a loss, a deduction of experience, or even Elo points.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] Certain games also have a 'disconnect delay' period before the player can disconnect that can last 10–30 seconds.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] This prevents a player from instantly disconnecting if they are about to die or lose.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] In some games, if a player disconnects they can receive a warning or even get locked out of online play for a short period.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] In many games, weapons can be fired in burst fire or single shot fire modes.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] Modifying a controller or keyboard/mouse to gain the advantage of having a faster firing weapon than the standard player can be considered a method of cheating.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] These modifications can create an imbalance within the game.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] In addition to modifying a console or its controller, it is possible to achieve a similar effect on the PC by binding the firing button to the scroll wheel of a mouse, or by using a macro setting that will simulate rapid key presses automatically.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] However, most games limit the rate at which weapons can be fired, regardless of how fast a player presses the button, in order to limit this form of cheating.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] Exploiting is the application of an unintended feature or bug that gives the player an advantage not intended by the game design.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] Exploiting is generally considered cheating by the gaming community at large due to the unfair advantage usually gained by the exploiter.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] Most software developers of online games prohibit exploiting in their terms of service and often issue sanctions against players found to be exploiting.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] There is some contention by exploiters that exploiting should not be considered cheating as it is merely taking advantage of actions allowed by the software.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] Some players view exploiting as a skill because certain exploits take a significant amount of time to find, or dexterity and timing to use.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] The term farming may refer to the practice of garnering achievements or virtual property for the purpose of real-money-trading.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] With rare exception, this has no direct effect on the gaming experience of other players; instead, it is a violation of most EULAs and could devalue the virtual property being farmed.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] Twinking is the act of transferring gear intended for higher level characters to lower level characters that would be incapable of obtaining the gear on their own.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] Twinked characters have a huge advantage over non-twinked characters, as well as the rest of the game world.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] This is usually used by players who wish to create a new character, either to help them level more rapidly or to gain an unfair advantage in PvP (*i.e.* player versus player, a type of multiplayer interactive conflict).
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] Most MMORPGs tolerate it, provided that the twinked character is not used in PvP combat against non-twinked characters.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] Often limits on twinking are placed into the game, usually through strict level or stat requirements to equip the item.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] Circumventing these level requirements would then be further cheating.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] Most games allow other participants to observe the game as it is played from a variety of perspectives; depending on the game, perspectives allow an observer a map overview or attach a "camera" to the movement of a specific player.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] In doing so, the observer can communicate with an accomplice using a secondary communication methodology (in-game private message, third party communication, or even off-line) to inform friendly players of traps or the position of opponents.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] An observer can be an active player, using a separate computer, connection and account.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] Some systems prevent inactive players from observing the game if they are on the same IP address as an active player, on the grounds that they are probably in close physical proximity; when all players from a single IP address are no longer active participants, they are all allowed to observe.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] Additionally, this may be used against players livestreaming to platforms like Twitch to observe the player and their team's position and stats.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] This is often referred to as stream sniping.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] Stacking involves altering game settings or team lineups to give one or more teams an unfair advantage over others.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] One example includes arranging a team composed of skilled or professional players against a team with members of lesser skill.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] Less ethical rigging involves weighting the game by providing a player or team with an advantage by outfitting them with better (or more familiar) weapons or equipment, or creating a play field that caters to a certain player, team or playing style.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] Many games prevent this by preventing players from joining a team with more players than the opposing side, forcing newcomers to balance the teams.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] Scripting is the use of a program or game feature to automate certain actions or behaviors.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] The use of scripts may or may not be considered cheating, depending on the behavior involved, and whether said behaviour is replicable without the use of such script.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] A script may give the user unusually fast firing rate, unobtainable otherwise, or may perform seemingly trivial tasks such as reloading.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] Some scripts can also tamper with other players' systems by spoofing commands.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] The cheat doesn't actually run on the gaming computer.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] Instead, the DMA card sends the game's memory data to a second computer via a cable.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] In the client–server model, the server is responsible for information security and enforcing game rules.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] "Never trust the client" is a maxim among game developers (as well as other developers) that summarizes the model of client–server game design.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] The server will be very fast, but any wallhack program will reveal where all the players in the game are, what team they are on, and what state they are in — health, weapon, ammo etc.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] At the same time, altered and erroneous data from a client will allow a player to break the game rules, manipulate the server, and even manipulate other clients.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] Many cheats are implemented by modifying and hooking code at runtime.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] There are two types of cheats implemented in this manner, internal and external.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] The principal difference between the two is how they interact with the game process.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] Internal cheats inject their code into the process, commonly via DLL injection, which allows them to read and write the process's entire address space and hook internal functions.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] On the other hand, external cheats run in a separate process with their own address space, and use the operating system's memory read/write primitives (such as `ReadProcessMemory` on Microsoft Windows) to modify the process's memory.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] Rather than modifying the game code (which the game itself or a 3rd-party protection system may detect), some cheats modify underlying system components.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] An example of this is graphics driver modifications that ignore depth checking and draw all objects on the screen—a primitive wallhack.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] System or driver modification is harder to detect, as there are a large number of system drivers that differ from user to user.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] The security of game software can be circumvented by intercepting and/or manipulating data (divided into "packets") in real-time while in transit from the client to the server or vice versa (i.e. a man-in-the-middle attack).
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] Interception can be passive or result in active manipulation; either method can be performed on the client machine itself or via an external communication proxy; some aimbots incorporate this method.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] Some computer and console devices sold under the guise of "accessibility peripherals" have been used to gain unfair advantages over other players of games, such as eliminating recoil completely and boosting aim assistance, and some may even include additionally downloadable macros.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] Some games use different pools for matchmaking purposes, for instance, PC players are matched with other PC players, and console players are matched with other console players.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] A console peripheral allowing the use of mouse and keyboard can be used to trick the console system to provide additional aim assistance provided to controllers.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] More sophisticated online video game cheaters use specialized DMA attack cards to access a game's memory, providing features such as seeing through walls.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] This method uses a second computer to analyze the memory dump without requiring any software modification on the computer that a game is running on, making it much harder to detect than conventional cheats.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] A mouse-emulator can then automatically aim and fire, implementing an aimbot.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] *Delta Force* is notorious for its tug-of-war between cheaters and Anti-Cheat Expert developers.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] There are many facets of cheating in online games which make the creation of a system to stop cheating very difficult; however, game developers and third-party software developers have created or are developing technologies that attempt to prevent cheating.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] Such countermeasures are commonly used in video games, with notable anti-cheat software being BattlEye, GameGuard, PunkBuster, Valve Anti-Cheat (specifically used on games on the Steam platform), and EasyAntiCheat.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] Generally, the better the server is at enforcing the rules, the less of a problem cheating will be in the game.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] In this approach, all client functionality either runs purely on the game server or alternatively the game server mirrors the client gameplay and continuously validates the game state.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] In many mobile games, it is a common practice to run the client game sessions synchronously on the server, using exactly the same user input.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] The client session is reset when the game sessions become unsynced, thereby preventing cheating.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] Server-side game code makes a trade-off between calculating and sending results for display on a just-in-time basis or trusting the client to calculate and display the results in appropriate sequence as a player progresses.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] Today however, with the increased speed and power of multi-core computers, lower-priced hardware, and the increased availability of broadband internet, this has become less of an issue.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] Additionally to storing data in non-standard formats, some games also utilize runtime protection through software protectors.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] The key target is to keep attackers from directly inspecting or modifying compiled software.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] Protectors utilize any of three methods to protect software.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] Encryption solutions will encrypt the code instructions and typically use a multi–layered defense mechanism against any reversing or tampering attempts that target the decryption code directly.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] Most protection systems in this category encrypt the code and then decrypt it at the application's startup or during runtime.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] This is the moment at which an attacker will breakpoint, reverse, and inject custom code.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] Runtime decryption may also add significant processing overhead and lower the game's framerate.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] Alternatively, some solutions focus on obfuscating the code by inserting jump statements and seemingly random instruction paths.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] The final and strongest alternative is virtualization.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] In this approach the encrypted code runs on a virtual CPU that can be markedly different from generic x86 and x64 CPUs as the instruction set can be unique for each protected file.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] The shared weakness of protectors and virtualizers is that they impact performance, either by requiring decryption or by introducing unnecessary CPU instructions.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] To reduce the overhead, code virtualizers are often only used to secure the critical parts of the code base, such as those interfacing with the game state and rendering.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] Spectator functionality can allow server administrators to monitor individual players and thereby determine whether or not a cheat is in place.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] One risk of the spectator mode is that in competitive matches the spectator could abuse the mode for spying on specific players and communicating player positions and tactics to the opposing team.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] Some games get around this limitation by not allowing spectator mode at all, or by delaying the video feed.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] Some games have systemized player supervision by allowing the community to review reports of disruptive behavior, determine whether those reports are valid, and apply temporary bans if appropriate.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] Reports can include data such as screenshots, videos, and chatlogs.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] Anomalies in player behavior can be detected by statistically analyzing game events sent by the client to the server.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] The benefit is that this anti–cheat method is non–intrusive to the player's privacy and guaranteed to work on all end–user system configurations.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] The restriction of this method is that it cannot always be clear whether or not a player is cheating.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] Highly skilled players can for example develop such a map sense that they may end up being flagged for the use of a wallhack and/or aimbot.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] On the other hand, players may also cheat in a way that is under the detection thresholds and remain uncaught.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] To reduce the amount of false positives, statistical detection systems are often combined with a supervision system that either is community driven or managed by a professional administrator team.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] In such implementations unusual player behavior can trigger a client-side component to create and upload reports for review.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] Pattern detection systems scan the player's hard drives and system memory for known cheat code or programs.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] Compared to statistical detection, the key advantage is that the subtle cheaters are also detected.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] Other than this, a pure pattern detection approach generally has few advantages.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] Experience has shown that keeping detection-based systems up to date is relatively slow and labor-intensive as one needs to constantly track down cheats and update detection patterns.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] End–users may also be concerned with privacy issues, such as has been the case with VAC (Valve Anti-Cheat) accessing browsing history.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] Sandboxing a software process can protect against potentially malicious actions such as code injection and memory modifications that would otherwise tamper with the game.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] One of the key benefits of sandboxing is that it can effectively prevent the underlying cheat mechanisms from working, and thereby can avoid the need for banning game community members as cheats simply do not work.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] Additionally, strong prevention mechanisms can stop many game hackers from targeting the game because of elevated skill requirements.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] Compared to pattern detection systems, sandboxing is generally not privacy invasive, as the approach requires no data to be uploaded to foreign back-end systems.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] Anti-cheat software commonly use low-level system interfaces not intended by the OS vendor for public use.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] As a result, they are a common source of incompatibilities with newer versions of operating systems and security measures as well as alternative OS API implementations such as Wine.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] For example, Windows enables Hypervisor-protected Code Integrity (HVCI) by default in every market except Chinese and Korean installations due to anti-cheat compatibility issues.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] Game publishers can implement a wide array of consequences for cheating players.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] Some game publishers may decide to try to permanently ban players who are persistent in cheating and disrupting the game community.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] Such bans are typically placed based on hardware ID or IP address.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] Consequently, cheaters may develop ways of getting around these bans, by either playing through proxy or VPN servers, or spoofing or changing their hardware configuration.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] Some companies and leagues ban suspected cheaters by blacklisting specific installation or serial keys, or user accounts, meaning that the player is effectively prevented from playing the game online.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] Certain games are known to identify cheaters and "shadow ban" them by placing them in matchmaking with other cheaters only, so as not to let the cheaters know that they have been identified.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] While game publishers are known to ban players employing cheats, the actual number of players banned is usually not revealed.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] Exceptions to this include Blizzard Entertainment, Nexon, and CipSoft, known for banning cheaters in batches, and publicising the number of banned accounts, presumably in order to discourage others from cheating.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] In some cases a ban may not be permanent and will expire after a certain period of time.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] Suspensions are commonly used as a punitive measure for abuse of game glitches, harassing players, or benefiting from hacks, and to discourage further violation of rules unless the user receive a permanent ban.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] Temporary bans may also be utilized in case a violation cannot be fully proven, as is common with anti-cheating methods based on supervision or statistical detection.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] In general kicking is perceived as a mild punishment, serving as a warning for the player in question.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] Some anti-cheat systems may decide to kick players out of a game server when the system integrity cannot be enforced nor be determined with certainty.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] Other anti-cheat methods may also utilize kicks as an instant punishment for presumably unfair game play behavior.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] Some games may also provide the community with the option of voting for particular players to be kicked.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] Even though vote kicking brings many benefits, it may also serve as a tool for trolling or griefing by allowing for legitimate players to be removed out of the game through the voting process.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] When a violation is the result of farming or stat-padding, it may be too severe of a punishment to suspend or ban players.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] Some games, therefore, implement a system of demotion in which the offender is moved to a lower rank (demoting), the opposite of a promotion.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] In several games where points are used, if a player is caught cheating they will get their score reset to the base value that is applied when a new player joins the server.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] In recent years, countries including South Korea and China have criminalized the sale or use of cheats in video games.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] In South Korea, cheaters could be punished with up to 5 years in jail or fines exceeding $40,000.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] The presence of cheaters in online games may push away the legitimate playerbase and reduce overall profits in the industry, leading to game developers working with legislative bodies or enforcement agencies.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] Historically, some game companies have also taken legal measures against individuals that have created and sold cheating tools in video games as a means to curb their use.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] Anti-cheat experts have argued that it is particularly important to take legal steps against entities who profit from making and selling cheats.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] In April 2013, coder DrUnKeN ChEeTaH was sued by Nexon America for operating GameAnarchy, a popular subscription based cheat provider for *Combat Arms*, and lost, Nexon being awarded $1.4 million in damages.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] In January 2017, Riot Games successfully sued the LeagueSharp service, which offered a subscription-based hacking service for Riot's *League of Legends*, with a $10 million award to be paid to Riot.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] Blizzard Entertainment sued Bossland GMBH for distributing software hacks for several of its games, and was awarded $8.5 million in damages.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] Epic Games, producers of the battle royale game *Fortnite* have sued two cheaters partnered with AddictedCheats, who offer cheating services for a variety of online games.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] Bungie had sued AimJunkies for cheats related to *Destiny 2*.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] Often, game company lawsuits against cheaters or cheat providers cite copyright infringement as the reason for the lawsuit.
[src:authoritative-server/cheating-in-online-games] While some argue against the merit of this claim, grounds for copyright infringement include damaging the company's intellectual property, affecting the experience of other users, and circumventing the Digital Millennium Copyright Act (DMCA), which could be applied to video games.
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] The **client–server model** is a form of messaging pattern in a distributed application structure that partitions tasks or workloads between the providers of a resource or service, called servers, and service requesters, called clients.
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] Often clients and servers communicate over a computer network on separate hardware, but both client and server may be on the same device.
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] A server host runs one or more server programs, which share their resources with clients.
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] A client usually does not share its computing resources, but it requests content or service from a server and may share its own content as part of the request.
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] Clients, therefore, initiate communication sessions with servers, which await incoming requests.
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] Examples of computer applications that use the client–server model are email, network printing, and the World Wide Web.
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] The server component provides a function or service to one or many clients, which initiate requests for such services.
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] Servers are classified by the services they provide.
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] For example, a web server serves web pages and a file server serves computer files.
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] A shared resource may be any of the server computer's software and electronic components, from programs and data to processors and storage devices.
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] The sharing of resources of a server constitutes a *service*.
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] Whether a computer is a client, a server, or both, is determined by the nature of the application that requires the service functions.
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] For example, a single computer can run a web server and file server software at the same time to serve different data to clients making different kinds of requests.
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] The client software can also communicate with server software within the same computer.
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] Communication between servers, such as to synchronize data, is sometimes called *inter-server* or *server-to-server* communication.
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] Generally, a service is an abstraction of computer resources and a client does not have to be concerned with how the server performs while fulfilling the request and delivering the response.
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] The client only has to understand the response based on the relevant application protocol, i.e. the content and the formatting of the data for the requested service.
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] Clients and servers exchange messages in a request–response messaging pattern.
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] The client sends a request, and the server returns a response.
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] This exchange of messages is an example of inter-process communication.
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] To communicate, the computers must have a common language, and they must follow rules so that both the client and the server know what to expect.
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] The language and rules of communication are defined in a communications protocol.
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] All protocols operate in the application layer.
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] The application layer protocol defines the basic patterns of the dialogue.
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] To formalize the data exchange even further, the server may implement an application programming interface (API).
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] The API is an abstraction layer for accessing a service.
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] By restricting communication to a specific content format, it facilitates parsing.
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] By abstracting access, it facilitates cross-platform data exchange.
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] A server may receive requests from many distinct clients in a short period.
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] A computer can only perform a limited number of tasks at any moment, and relies on a scheduling system to prioritize incoming requests from clients to accommodate them.
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] To prevent abuse and maximize availability, the server software may limit the availability to clients.
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] Denial of service attacks are designed to exploit a server's obligation to process requests by overloading it with excessive request rates.
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] Encryption should be applied if sensitive information is to be communicated between the client and the server.
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] When a bank customer accesses online banking services with a web browser (the client), the client initiates a request to the bank's web server.
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] The customer's login credentials are compared against a database, and the webserver accesses that database server as a client.
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] An application server interprets the returned data by applying the bank's business logic and provides the output to the webserver.
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] Finally, the webserver returns the result to the client web browser for display.
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] In each step of this sequence of client–server message exchanges, a computer processes a request and returns data.
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] This is the request-response messaging pattern.
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] When all the requests are met, the sequence is complete.
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] This example illustrates a design pattern applicable to the client–server model: separation of concerns.
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] Server-side refers to programs and operations that run on the server.
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] This is in contrast to client-side programs and operations which run on the client.
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] "Server-side software" refers to a computer application, such as a web server, that runs on remote server hardware, reachable from a user's local computer, smartphone, or other device.
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] Operations may be performed server-side because they require access to information or functionality that is not available on the client, or because performing such operations on the client side would be slow, unreliable, or insecure.
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] Client and server programs may be commonly available ones such as free or commercial web servers and web browsers, communicating with each other using standardized protocols.
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] Or, programmers may write their own server, client, and communications protocol which can only be used with one another.
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] Server-side operations include both those that are carried out in response to client requests, and non-client-oriented operations such as maintenance tasks.
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] In a computer security context, server-side vulnerabilities or attacks refer to those that occur on a server computer system, rather than on the client side, or in between the two.
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] For example, an attacker might exploit an SQL injection vulnerability in a web application in order to maliciously change or gain unauthorized access to data in the server's database.
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] Alternatively, an attacker might break into a server system using vulnerabilities in the underlying operating system and then be able to access database and other files in the same manner as authorized administrators of the server.
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] In the case of an Internet-dependent user application like Google Earth, while querying and display of map data takes place on the client side, the server is responsible for permanent storage of map data, resolving user queries into map data to be returned to the client, etc.
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] Web applications and services can be implemented in almost any language, as long as they can return data to standards-based web browsers (possibly via intermediary programs) in formats which they can use.
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] Client-side refers to operations that are performed by the client in a computer network.
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] Typically, a client is a computer application, such as a web browser, that runs on a user's local computer, smartphone, or other device, and connects to a server as necessary.
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] Additionally, if operations can be performed by the client, without sending data over the network, they may take less time, use less bandwidth, and incur a lesser security risk.
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] When the server serves data in a commonly used manner, for example according to standard protocols such as HTTP or FTP, users may have their choice of a number of client programs (e.g. most modern web browsers can request and receive data using both HTTP and FTP).
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] In the case of more specialized applications, programmers may write their own server, client, and communications protocol which can only be used with one another.
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] Programs that run on a user's local computer without ever sending or receiving data over a network are not considered clients, and so the operations of such programs would not be termed client-side operations.
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] In a computer security context, client-side vulnerabilities or attacks refer to those that occur on the client / user's computer system, rather than on the server side, or in between the two.
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] As an example, if a server contained an encrypted file or message which could only be decrypted using a key housed on the user's computer system, a client-side attack would normally be an attacker's only opportunity to gain access to the decrypted contents.
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] For instance, the attacker might cause malware to be installed on the client system, allowing the attacker to view the user's screen, record the user's keystrokes, and steal copies of the user's encryption keys, etc.
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] Alternatively, an attacker might employ cross-site scripting vulnerabilities to execute malicious code on the client's system without needing to install any permanently resident malware.
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] Distributed computing projects such as SETI@home and the Great Internet Mersenne Prime Search, as well as Internet-dependent applications like Google Earth, rely primarily on client-side operations.
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] They initiate a connection with the server (either in response to a user query, as with Google Earth, or in an automated fashion, as with SETI@home), and request some data.
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] The server selects a data set (a server-side operation) and sends it back to the client.
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] The client then analyzes the data (a client-side operation), and, when the analysis is complete, displays it to the user (as with Google Earth) and/or transmits the results of calculations back to the server (as with SETI@home).
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] An early form of client–server architecture is remote job entry, dating at least to OS/360 (announced 1964), where the request was to run a job, and the response was the output.
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] While formulating the client–server model in the 1960s and 1970s, computer scientists building ARPANET (at the Stanford Research Institute) used the terms *server-host* (or *serving host*) and *user-host* (or *using-host*), and these appear in the early documents RFC 5 and RFC 4.
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] This usage was continued at Xerox PARC in the mid-1970s.
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] One context in which researchers used these terms was in the design of a computer network programming language called Decode-Encode Language (DEL).
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] The purpose of this language was to accept commands from one computer (the user-host), which would return status reports to the user as it encoded the commands in network packets.
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] Another DEL-capable computer, the server-host, received the packets, decoded them, and returned formatted data to the user-host.
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] A DEL program on the user-host received the results to present to the user.
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] Development of DEL was just beginning in 1969, the year that the United States Department of Defense established ARPANET (predecessor of Internet).
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] An early use of the word *client* occurs in "Separating Data from Function in a Distributed File System", a 1978 paper by Xerox PARC computer scientists Howard Sturgis, James Mitchell, and Jay Israel.
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] The authors are careful to define the term for readers, and explain that they use it to distinguish between the user and the user's network node (the client).
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] By 1992, the word *server* had entered into general parlance.
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] The client-server model does not dictate that server-hosts must have more resources than client-hosts.
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] Rather, it enables any general-purpose computer to extend its capabilities by using the shared resources of other hosts.
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] Centralized computing, however, specifically allocates a large number of resources to a small number of computers.
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] The more computation is offloaded from client-hosts to the central computers, the simpler the client-hosts can be.
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] It relies heavily on network resources (servers and infrastructure) for computation and storage.
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] A diskless node loads even its operating system from the network, and a computer terminal has no operating system at all; it is only an input/output interface to the server.
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] In contrast, a rich client, such as a personal computer, has many resources and does not rely on a server for essential functions.
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] As microcomputers decreased in price and increased in power from the 1980s to the late 1990s, many organizations transitioned computation from centralized servers, such as mainframes and minicomputers, to rich clients.
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] This afforded greater, more individualized dominion over computer resources, but complicated information technology management.
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] During the 2000s, web applications matured enough to rival application software developed for a specific microarchitecture.
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] This maturation, more affordable mass storage, and the advent of service-oriented architecture were among the factors that gave rise to the cloud computing trend of the 2010s.
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] In addition to the client-server model, distributed computing applications often use the peer-to-peer (P2P) application architecture.
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] In the client-server model, the server is often designed to operate as a centralized system that serves many clients.
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] The computing power, memory and storage requirements of a server must be scaled appropriately to the expected workload.
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] Load-balancing and failover systems are often employed to scale the server beyond a single physical machine.
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] Load balancing is defined as the methodical and efficient distribution of network or application traffic across multiple servers in a server farm.
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] Each load balancer sits between client devices and backend servers, receiving and then distributing incoming requests to any available server capable of fulfilling them.
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] In a peer-to-peer network, two or more computers (*peers*) pool their resources and communicate in a decentralized system.
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] Peers are coequal, or equipotent nodes in a non-hierarchical network.
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] Unlike clients in a client-server or client-queue-client network, peers communicate with each other directly.
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] In peer-to-peer networking, an algorithm in the peer-to-peer communications protocol balances load, and even peers with modest resources can help to share the load.
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] If a node becomes unavailable, its shared resources remain available as long as other peers offer it.
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] Ideally, a peer does not need to achieve high availability because other, redundant peers make up for any resource downtime; as the availability and load capacity of peers change, the protocol reroutes requests.
[src:authoritative-server/client-server-model] Both client-server and master-slave are regarded as sub-categories of distributed peer-to-peer systems.
[src:authoritative-server/multiplayer-video-game] Due to multiplayer games allowing players to interact with other individuals, they provide an element of social communication absent from single-player games.
[src:authoritative-server/multiplayer-video-game] The history of multiplayer video games extends over several decades, tracing back to the emergence of electronic gaming in the mid-20th century.
[src:authoritative-server/multiplayer-video-game] One of the earliest instances of multiplayer interaction was witnessed with the development of *Spacewar!* in 1962 for the DEC PDP-1 computer by Steve Russell and colleagues at the MIT.
[src:authoritative-server/multiplayer-video-game] During the late 1970s and early 1980s, multiplayer gaming gained momentum within the arcade scene with classics like *Pong* and *Tank*.
[src:authoritative-server/multiplayer-video-game] The transition to home gaming consoles in the 1980s further popularized multiplayer gaming.
[src:authoritative-server/multiplayer-video-game] Titles like *Super Mario Bros.* for the NES and *Golden Axe* for the Sega Genesis introduced cooperative and competitive gameplay.
[src:authoritative-server/multiplayer-video-game] Additionally, LAN gaming emerged in the late 1980s, enabling players to connect multiple computers for multiplayer gameplay, popularized by titles like *Doom* and *Warcraft: Orcs & Humans*.
[src:authoritative-server/multiplayer-video-game] Players can also play together in the same room using splitscreen.
[src:authoritative-server/multiplayer-video-game] Some of the earliest video games were two-player games, including early sports games (such as 1958's *Tennis For Two* and 1972's *Pong*), early shooter games such as *Spacewar!* (1962) and early racing video games such as *Astro Race* (1973).
[src:authoritative-server/multiplayer-video-game] The first examples of multiplayer real-time games were developed on the PLATO system about 1973.
[src:authoritative-server/multiplayer-video-game] Multi-user games developed on this system included 1973's Empire and 1974's Spasim; the latter was an early first-person shooter.
[src:authoritative-server/multiplayer-video-game] Other early video games included turn-based multiplayer modes, popular in tabletop arcade machines.
[src:authoritative-server/multiplayer-video-game] In such games, play is alternated at some point (often after the loss of a life).
[src:authoritative-server/multiplayer-video-game] All players' scores are often displayed onscreen so players can see their relative standing.
[src:authoritative-server/multiplayer-video-game] Danielle Bunten Berry created some of the first multiplayer video games, such as her debut, *Wheeler Dealers* (1978) and her most notable work, *M.U.L.E.* (1983).
[src:authoritative-server/multiplayer-video-game] Kemeny wrote in 1972 that software running on the Dartmouth Time-Sharing System (DTSS) had recently gained the ability to support multiple simultaneous users, and that games were the first use of the functionality.
[src:authoritative-server/multiplayer-video-game] DTSS's popular American football game, he said, now supported head-to-head play by two humans.
[src:authoritative-server/multiplayer-video-game] The university's computer system had hundreds of terminals, connected (via serial lines) through cluster PDP-11s for student, teacher, and staff access.
[src:authoritative-server/multiplayer-video-game] The games had a program running on each terminal (for each player), sharing a segment of shared memory (known as the "high segment" in the OS TOPS-10).
[src:authoritative-server/multiplayer-video-game] The games became popular, and the university often banned them because of their RAM use.
[src:authoritative-server/multiplayer-video-game] STAR was based on 1974's single-user, turn-oriented BASIC program STAR, written by Michael O'Shaughnessy at UNH.
[src:authoritative-server/multiplayer-video-game] Wasserman and Stryker in 1980 described in *BYTE* how to network two Commodore PET computers with a cable.
[src:authoritative-server/multiplayer-video-game] Their article includes a type-in, two-player Hangman, and describes the authors' more-sophisticated *Flash Attack*.
[src:authoritative-server/multiplayer-video-game] SuperSet Software's *Snipes* (1981) uses networking technology that would become Novell NetWare.
[src:authoritative-server/multiplayer-video-game] Digital Equipment Corporation distributed another multi-user version of *Star Trek*, Decwar, without real-time screen updating; it was widely distributed to universities with DECsystem-10s.
[src:authoritative-server/multiplayer-video-game] In 1981 Cliff Zimmerman wrote an homage to *Star Trek* in MACRO-10 for DECsystem-10s and -20s using VT100-series graphics.
[src:authoritative-server/multiplayer-video-game] "VTtrek" pitted four Federation players against four Klingons in a three-dimensional universe.
[src:authoritative-server/multiplayer-video-game] Networked multiplayer gaming modes are known as "netplay".
[src:authoritative-server/multiplayer-video-game] The first popular video-game title with a Local Area Network(LAN) version, 1991's Spectre for the Apple Macintosh, featured AppleTalk support for up to eight players.
[src:authoritative-server/multiplayer-video-game] Spectre's popularity was partially attributed to the display of a player's name above their cybertank.
[src:authoritative-server/multiplayer-video-game] There followed 1993's Doom, whose first network version allowed four simultaneous players.
[src:authoritative-server/multiplayer-video-game] Play-by-email multiplayer games use email to communicate between computers.
[src:authoritative-server/multiplayer-video-game] Other turn-based variations not requiring players to be online simultaneously are Play-by-post gaming and Play-by-Internet.
[src:authoritative-server/multiplayer-video-game] Some online games are "massively multiplayer", with many players participating simultaneously.
[src:authoritative-server/multiplayer-video-game] Two massively multiplayer genres are MMORPG (such as *World of Warcraft* or *EverQuest*) and MMORTS.
[src:authoritative-server/multiplayer-video-game] First-person shooters have become popular multiplayer games; *Battlefield 1942* and *Counter-Strike* have little (or no) single-player gameplay.
[src:authoritative-server/multiplayer-video-game] Developer and gaming site OMGPOP's library included multiplayer Flash games for the casual player until it was shut down in 2013.
[src:authoritative-server/multiplayer-video-game] Some networked multiplayer games, including MUDs and massively multiplayer online games (MMOs) such as RuneScape, omit a single-player mode.
[src:authoritative-server/multiplayer-video-game] The largest MMO in 2008 was *World of Warcraft*, with over 10 million registered players worldwide.
[src:authoritative-server/multiplayer-video-game] *World of Warcraft* would hit its peak at 12 million players two years later in 2010, and in 2023 earned the Guinness World Record for best selling MMO video game.
[src:authoritative-server/multiplayer-video-game] This category of games requires multiple machines to connect via the Internet; before the Internet became popular, MUDs were played on time-sharing computer systems and games like *Doom* were played on a LAN.
[src:authoritative-server/multiplayer-video-game] Beginning with the Sega NetLink in 1996, Game.com in 1997 and Dreamcast in 2000, game consoles support network gaming over LANs and the Internet.
[src:authoritative-server/multiplayer-video-game] Many mobile phones and handheld consoles also offer wireless gaming with Bluetooth (or similar) technology.
[src:authoritative-server/multiplayer-video-game] By the early 2010s online gaming had become a mainstay of console platforms such as Xbox and PlayStation.
[src:authoritative-server/multiplayer-video-game] During the 2010s, as the number of Internet users increased, two new video game genres rapidly gained worldwide popularity – multiplayer online battle arena and battle royale game, both designed exclusively for multiplayer gameplay over the Internet.
[src:authoritative-server/multiplayer-video-game] Over time the number of people playing video games has increased.
[src:authoritative-server/multiplayer-video-game] In 2020, the majority of households in the United States have an occupant that plays video games, and 65% of gamers play multiplayer games with others either online or in person.
[src:authoritative-server/multiplayer-video-game] For some games, "multiplayer" implies that players are playing on the same gaming system or network.
[src:authoritative-server/multiplayer-video-game] This applies to all arcade games, but also to a number of console, and personal computer games too.
[src:authoritative-server/multiplayer-video-game] Turn-based games such as chess also lend themselves to single system single screen and even to a single controller.
[src:authoritative-server/multiplayer-video-game] Multiple types of games allow players to use local multiplayer.
[src:authoritative-server/multiplayer-video-game] The term "local co-op" or "couch co-op" refers to local multiplayer games played in a cooperative manner on the same system; these may use split-screen or some other display method.
[src:authoritative-server/multiplayer-video-game] Hot-seat games are typically turn-based games with only one controller or input set – such as a single keyboard/mouse on the system.
[src:authoritative-server/multiplayer-video-game] Players rotate using the input device to perform their turn such that each is taking a turn on the "hot-seat".
[src:authoritative-server/multiplayer-video-game] Not all local multiplayer games are played on the same console or personal computer.
[src:authoritative-server/multiplayer-video-game] Some local multiplayer games are played over a LAN.
[src:authoritative-server/multiplayer-video-game] This involves multiple devices using one local network to play together.
[src:authoritative-server/multiplayer-video-game] Networked multiplayer games on LAN eliminate common problems faced when playing online such as lag and anonymity.
[src:authoritative-server/multiplayer-video-game] Games played on a LAN network are the focus of LAN parties.
[src:authoritative-server/multiplayer-video-game] While local co-op and LAN parties still take place, there has been a decrease in both due to an increasing number of players and games utilizing online multiplayer gaming.
[src:authoritative-server/multiplayer-video-game] Online multiplayer games connect players over a wide area network (a common example being the Internet).
[src:authoritative-server/multiplayer-video-game] Unlike local multiplayer, players playing online multiplayer are not restricted to the same local network.
[src:authoritative-server/multiplayer-video-game] This allows players to interact with others from a much greater distance.
[src:authoritative-server/multiplayer-video-game] Playing multiplayer online offers the benefits of distance, but it also comes with its own unique challenges.
[src:authoritative-server/multiplayer-video-game] Gamers refer to latency using the term "ping", after a utility which measures round-trip network communication delays (by the use of ICMP packets).
[src:authoritative-server/multiplayer-video-game] A player on a DSL connection with a 50-ms ping can react faster than a modem user with a 350-ms average latency.
[src:authoritative-server/multiplayer-video-game] Other problems include packet loss and choke, which can prevent a player from "registering" their actions with a server.
[src:authoritative-server/multiplayer-video-game] In first-person shooters, this problem appears when bullets hit the enemy without damage.
[src:authoritative-server/multiplayer-video-game] The player's connection is not the only factor; some servers are slower than others.
[src:authoritative-server/multiplayer-video-game] A server that is geographically closer to the player's connection will often provide a lower ping.
[src:authoritative-server/multiplayer-video-game] Data packets travel faster to a location that is closer to them.
[src:authoritative-server/multiplayer-video-game] How far the device is from an internet connection (router) can also affect latency.
[src:authoritative-server/multiplayer-video-game] Asymmetrical multiplayer is a type of gameplay in which players can have significantly different roles or abilities from each other – enough to provide a significantly different experience of the game.
[src:authoritative-server/multiplayer-video-game] A first-person shooter that adopts the asymmetrical multiplayer system is Tom Clancy's Rainbow Six Siege.
[src:authoritative-server/multiplayer-video-game] Giving players their own special operator changes every player's experience.
[src:authoritative-server/multiplayer-video-game] This puts an emphasis on players improvising their own game plan given the abilities their character has.
[src:authoritative-server/multiplayer-video-game] In games with stronger elements of asymmetry, one player/team may have one gameplay experience (or be in softly asymmetric roles) while the other player or team play in a drastically different way, with different mechanics, a different type of objective, or both.
[src:authoritative-server/multiplayer-video-game] Examples of games with strong asymmetry include *Dead by Daylight*, *Evolve*, and *Left 4 Dead*.
[src:authoritative-server/multiplayer-video-game] Deathloop featured opt‑in asymmetric PvP and Elden Ring’s evolved Souls invasions at scale.
[src:authoritative-server/multiplayer-video-game] Depending on the game, objectives and story, the invading player(s) goals, roles, and own objectives will be different.
[src:authoritative-server/multiplayer-video-game] Asynchronous multiplayer is a form of multiplayer gameplay where players are not necessarily playing at the same time.
[src:authoritative-server/multiplayer-video-game] This form of multiplayer game has its origins in play-by-mail games, where players would send their moves through postal mail to a game master, who then would compile and send out results for the next turn.
[src:authoritative-server/multiplayer-video-game] Play-by-mail games transitioned to electronic form as play-by-email games.
[src:authoritative-server/multiplayer-video-game] Similar games were developed for bulletin board systems, such as *Trade Wars*, where the turn structure may not be as rigorous and allow players to take actions at any time in a persistence space alongside all other players, a concept known as sporadic play.
[src:authoritative-server/multiplayer-video-game] These types of asynchronous multiplayer games waned with the widespread availability of the Internet which allowed players to play against each other simultaneously, but remains an option in many strategy-related games, such as the *Civilization* series.
[src:authoritative-server/multiplayer-video-game] Coordination of turns are subsequently managed by one computer or a centralized server.
[src:authoritative-server/multiplayer-video-game] Further, many mobile games are based on sporadic play and use social interactions with other players, lacking direct player versus player game modes but allowing players to influence other players' games, coordinated through central game servers, another facet of asynchronous play.
[src:authoritative-server/multiplayer-video-game] Online cheating (in gaming) usually refers to modifying the game experience to give one player an advantage over others, such as using an "aimbot" – a program which automatically locks the player's crosshairs onto a target – in shooting games.
[src:authoritative-server/multiplayer-video-game] This is also known as "hacking" or "glitching" ("glitching" refers to using a glitch, or a mistake in the code of a game, whereas "hacking" is manipulating the code of a game).
[src:authoritative-server/multiplayer-video-game] Cheating in video games is often done via a third-party program that modifies the game's code at runtime to give one or more players an advantage.
[src:authoritative-server/multiplayer-video-game] In other situations, it is frequently done by changing the game's files to change the game's mechanics.
[src:authoritative-server/netcode] Players often blame "bad netcode" when they experience lag or reverse state transitions when synchronization between players is lost.
[src:authoritative-server/netcode] Although these events are sometimes caused by bugs, other networking-related causes include high latency between server and client, packet loss, or network congestion.
[src:authoritative-server/netcode] Depending on the game implementation, these issues can also be caused by non-network factors such as frame rendering time or inconsistent frame rate.
[src:authoritative-server/netcode] Netcode is often designed to mask networking irregularities and create a synchronous and smooth gamestate across multiple users.
[src:authoritative-server/netcode] There are two main resolutions to this conflict implemented in modern games: delay-based and rollback-based resolution.
[src:authoritative-server/netcode] The classic solution to this problem is the use of a delay-based netcode.
[src:authoritative-server/netcode] When the inputs of a remote player arrive late, the game delays the inputs of the local player accordingly to synchronize the two inputs and run them simultaneously.
[src:authoritative-server/netcode] This added delay can be disruptive for players (especially when latency is high), but overall the change is not very noticeable.
[src:authoritative-server/netcode] However, these delays can be inconsistent due to sudden fluctuations in current latency.
[src:authoritative-server/netcode] Should the latency between players exceed an established buffer window for the remote player, the game must wait, causing the screens to "freeze".
[src:authoritative-server/netcode] This occurs because a delay-based netcode does not allow the simulation to continue until it receives the inputs from all the players in the frame in question.
[src:authoritative-server/netcode] This variable delay causes an inconsistent and unresponsive experience compared to offline play (or to a LAN game), and can negatively affect player performance in timing-sensitive and fast-paced genres such as fighting games.
[src:authoritative-server/netcode] An alternative system to the previous netcode is rollback netcode.
[src:authoritative-server/netcode] Some games utilize a hybrid solution in order to disguise these "jumps" (which can become problematic as latency between players grows, as there is less and less time to react to other players' actions) with a fixed input delay and then rollback being used.
[src:authoritative-server/netcode] Rollback is quite effective at concealing lag spikes or other issues related to inconsistencies in the users' connections, as predictions are often correct and players do not even notice.
[src:authoritative-server/netcode] Nevertheless, this system can be troublesome whenever a client's game slows down (usually due to overheating), since rift problems can be caused leading to an exchange of tickets between machines at unequal rates.
[src:authoritative-server/netcode] This generates visual glitches that interrupt the gameplay of those players that receive inputs at a slower pace, while the player whose game is slowed down will have an advantage over the rest by receiving inputs from others at a normal rate (this is known as one-sided rollback).
[src:authoritative-server/netcode] There is a popular MIT-licensed library named GGPO designed to help implement rollback networking to games (mainly fighting games).
[src:authoritative-server/netcode] Latency is unavoidable in online games, and the quality of the player's experience is strictly tied to this (the more latency there is between players, the greater the feeling that the game is not responsive to their inputs).
[src:authoritative-server/netcode] The latency of the players' network (which is largely out of a game's control) is not the only factor in question, but also the latency inherent in the way the game simulations are run.
[src:authoritative-server/netcode] There are several lag compensation methods used to disguise or cope with latency (especially with high latency values).
[src:authoritative-server/netcode] A single update of a game simulation is known as a tick.
[src:authoritative-server/netcode] The rate at which the simulation is run on a server is often referred to as the server's tickrate; this is essentially the server equivalent of a client's frame rate, absent any rendering system.
[src:authoritative-server/netcode] Tickrate is limited by the length of time it takes to run the simulation, and is often intentionally limited further to reduce instability introduced by a fluctuating tickrate, and to reduce CPU and data transmission costs.
[src:authoritative-server/netcode] A lower tickrate increases latency in the synchronization of the game simulation between the server and clients.
[src:authoritative-server/netcode] A lower tickrate also naturally reduces the precision of the simulation, which itself might cause problems if taken too far, or if the client and server simulations are running at significantly different rates.
[src:authoritative-server/netcode] Because of limitations in the amount of available bandwidth and the CPU time that's taken by network communication, some games prioritize certain vital communications while limiting the frequency and priority of less important information.
[src:authoritative-server/netcode] As with tickrate, this effectively increases synchronization latency.
[src:authoritative-server/netcode] Game engines may limit the number of times that updates (of a simulation) are sent to a particular client and/or particular objects in the game's world in addition to reducing the precision of some values sent over the network to help with bandwidth use.
[src:authoritative-server/netcode] This lack of precision may in some instances be noticeable.
[src:authoritative-server/netcode] Various simulation synchronization errors between machines can also fall under the "netcode issues" blanket.
[src:authoritative-server/netcode] These may include bugs which cause the simulation to proceed differently on one machine than on another, or which cause some things to not be communicated when the user perceives that they ought to be.
[src:authoritative-server/netcode] A game's choice of transport layer protocol (and its management and coding) can also affect perceived networking issues.
[src:authoritative-server/netcode] If a game uses Transmission Control Protocol (TCP), there will be increased latency between players.
[src:authoritative-server/netcode] This protocol is based on the connection between two machines, in which they can exchange data and read it.
[src:authoritative-server/netcode] These types of connections are very reliable, stable, ordered and easy to implement.
[src:authoritative-server/netcode] This type of protocol also tends to respond very slowly whenever they lose a packet, or when packets arrive in an incorrect order or duplicated, which can be very detrimental to a real-time online game (this protocol was not designed for this type of software).
[src:authoritative-server/netcode] If the game instead uses a User Datagram Protocol (UDP), the connection between machines will be very fast, because instead of establishing a connection between them the data will be sent and received directly.
[src:authoritative-server/network-architecture] In telecommunications, the specification of a network architecture may also include a detailed description of products and services delivered via a communications network, as well as detailed rate and billing structures under which services are compensated.
[src:authoritative-server/network-architecture] The network architecture of the Internet is predominantly expressed by its use of the Internet protocol suite, rather than a specific model for interconnecting networks or nodes in the network, or the usage of specific types of hardware links.
[src:authoritative-server/network-architecture] The Open Systems Interconnection model (OSI model) defines and codifies the concept of layered network architecture.
[src:authoritative-server/network-architecture] Abstraction layers are used to subdivide a communications system further into smaller manageable parts.
[src:authoritative-server/network-architecture] A layer is a collection of similar functions that provide services to the layer above it and receives services from the layer below it.
[src:authoritative-server/network-architecture] On each layer, an instance provides services to the instances at the layer above and requests services from the layer below.
[src:authoritative-server/network-architecture] In distributed computing, the *network architecture* often describes the structure and classification of a distributed application architecture, as the participating nodes in a distributed application are often referred to as a *network*.
[src:authoritative-server/network-architecture] For example, the applications architecture of the public switched telephone network (PSTN) has been termed the Intelligent Network.
[src:authoritative-server/network-architecture] There are a number of specific classifications but all lie on a continuum between the dumb network (e.g. the Internet) and the intelligent network (e.g. the PSTN).
[src:authoritative-server/network-architecture] A popular example of such usage of the term in distributed applications, as well as permanent virtual circuits, is the organization of nodes in peer-to-peer (P2P) services and networks.
[src:authoritative-server/network-architecture] P2P networks usually implement overlay networks running over an underlying physical or logical network.
[src:authoritative-server/network-architecture] These overlay networks may implement certain organizational structures of the nodes according to several distinct models, the network architecture of the system.
[src:authoritative-server/server-computing] A **server** is a computer or software system that provides data, resources, or services to other computers called "clients" on a computer network.
[src:authoritative-server/server-computing] This architecture is called the client–server model.
[src:authoritative-server/server-computing] Servers can provide various functionalities, often called "services", such as sharing data or resources among multiple clients or performing computations for a client.
[src:authoritative-server/server-computing] A single server can serve multiple clients, and a single client can use multiple servers.
[src:authoritative-server/server-computing] A client process may run on the same device or may connect over a network to a server on a different device.
[src:authoritative-server/server-computing] Typical servers are database servers, file servers, mail servers, print servers, web servers, game servers, and application servers.
[src:authoritative-server/server-computing] Client–server systems are most frequently implemented by (and often identified with) the request–response model: a client sends a request to the server, which performs some action and sends a response back to the client, typically with a result or acknowledgment.
[src:authoritative-server/server-computing] Designating a computer as "server-class hardware" implies that it is specialized for running servers on it.
[src:authoritative-server/server-computing] This often implies that it is more powerful and reliable than standard personal computers.
[src:authoritative-server/server-computing] However, large computing clusters may also be composed of many relatively simple, replaceable server components.
[src:authoritative-server/server-computing] The use of the word *server* in computing comes from queueing theory, where it dates to the mid 20th century, being notably used in Kendall (1953) (along with "service"), the paper that introduced Kendall's notation.
[src:authoritative-server/server-computing] In earlier papers, such as the Erlang (1909), more concrete terms such as "[telephone] operators" are used.
[src:authoritative-server/server-computing] In computing, "server" dates at least to RFC 5 (1969), one of the earliest documents describing ARPANET (the predecessor of Internet), and is contrasted with "user", distinguishing two types of host: "server-host" and "user-host".
[src:authoritative-server/server-computing] The use of "serving" also dates to early documents, such as RFC 4, contrasting "serving-host" with "using-host".
[src:authoritative-server/server-computing] The average utilization of a server in the early 2000s was 5 to 15%, but with the adoption of virtualization this figure started to increase the number of servers needed.
[src:authoritative-server/server-computing] Strictly speaking, the term *server* refers to a computer program or process (running program).
[src:authoritative-server/server-computing] Through metonymy, it refers to a device used for (or a device dedicated to) running one or several server programs.
[src:authoritative-server/server-computing] On a network, such a device is called a *host*.
[src:authoritative-server/server-computing] In addition to *server*, the words *serve* and *service* (as verb and as noun respectively) are frequently used, though *servicer* and *servant* are not.
[src:authoritative-server/server-computing] The word *service* (noun) may refer to the abstract form of functionality, e.g.
[src:authoritative-server/server-computing] Alternatively, it may refer to a computer program that turns a computer into a server, e.g.
[src:authoritative-server/server-computing] Originally used as "servers serve users" (and "users use servers"), in the sense of "obey", today one often says that "servers serve data", in the same sense as "give".
[src:authoritative-server/server-computing] For instance, web servers "serve [up] web pages to users" or "service their requests".
[src:authoritative-server/server-computing] The server is part of the client–server model; in this model, a server serves data for clients.
[src:authoritative-server/server-computing] The nature of communication between a client and server is request and response.
[src:authoritative-server/server-computing] This is in contrast with peer-to-peer model in which the relationship is on-demand reciprocation.
[src:authoritative-server/server-computing] In principle, any computerized process that can be used or called by another process (particularly remotely, particularly to share a resource) is a server, and the calling process or processes is a client.
[src:authoritative-server/server-computing] Thus any general-purpose computer connected to a network can host servers.
[src:authoritative-server/server-computing] For example, if files on a device are shared by some process, that process is a file server.
[src:authoritative-server/server-computing] Similarly, web server software can *run* on any capable computer, and so a laptop or a personal computer can host a web server.
[src:authoritative-server/server-computing] While request–response is the most common client-server design, there are others, such as the publish–subscribe pattern.
[src:authoritative-server/server-computing] In the publish-subscribe pattern, clients register with a pub-sub server, subscribing to specified types of messages; this initial registration may be done by request-response.
[src:authoritative-server/server-computing] Thereafter, the pub-sub server forwards matching messages to the clients *without* any further requests: the server *pushes* messages to the client, rather than the client *pulling* messages from the server as in request-response.
[src:authoritative-server/server-computing] The role of a server is to share data as well as to share resources and distribute work.
[src:authoritative-server/server-computing] A server computer can serve its own computer programs as well; depending on the scenario, this could be part of a *quid pro quo* transaction, or simply a technical possibility.
[src:authoritative-server/server-computing] The following table shows several scenarios in which a server is used.
[src:authoritative-server/server-computing] Almost the entire structure of the Internet is based upon a client–server model.
[src:authoritative-server/server-computing] High-level root nameservers, DNS, and routers direct the traffic on the internet.
[src:authoritative-server/server-computing] There are millions of servers connected to the Internet, running continuously throughout the world and virtually every action taken by an ordinary Internet user requires one or more interactions with one or more servers.
[src:authoritative-server/server-computing] There are exceptions that do not use dedicated servers; for example, peer-to-peer file sharing and some implementations of telephony (e.g. pre-Microsoft Skype).
[src:authoritative-server/server-computing] Hardware requirement for servers vary widely, depending on the server's purpose and its software.
[src:authoritative-server/server-computing] Servers often are more powerful and expensive than the clients that connect to them.
[src:authoritative-server/server-computing] The name server is used both for the hardware and software pieces.
[src:authoritative-server/server-computing] For the hardware servers, it is usually limited to mean the high-end machines although software servers can run on a variety of hardwares.
[src:authoritative-server/server-computing] Since servers are usually accessed over a network, many run unattended without a computer monitor or input device, audio hardware and USB interfaces.
[src:authoritative-server/server-computing] Many servers do not have a graphical user interface (GUI).
[src:authoritative-server/server-computing] They are configured and managed remotely.
[src:authoritative-server/server-computing] Remote management can be conducted via various methods including Microsoft Management Console (MMC), PowerShell, SSH and browser-based out-of-band management systems such as Dell's iDRAC or HP's iLo.
[src:authoritative-server/server-computing] Large traditional single servers would need to be run for long periods without interruption.
[src:authoritative-server/server-computing] Availability would have to be very high, making hardware reliability and durability extremely important.
[src:authoritative-server/server-computing] Mission-critical enterprise servers would be very fault tolerant and use specialized hardware with low failure rates in order to maximize uptime.
[src:authoritative-server/server-computing] Uninterruptible power supplies might be incorporated to guard against power failure.
[src:authoritative-server/server-computing] Servers typically include hardware redundancy such as dual power supplies, RAID disk systems, and ECC memory, along with extensive pre-boot memory testing and verification.
[src:authoritative-server/server-computing] Critical components might be hot swappable, allowing technicians to replace them on the running server without shutting it down, and to guard against overheating, servers might have more powerful fans or use water cooling.
[src:authoritative-server/server-computing] They will often be able to be configured, powered up and down, or rebooted remotely, using out-of-band management, typically based on IPMI.
[src:authoritative-server/server-computing] Server casings are usually flat and wide, and designed to be rack-mounted, either on 19-inch racks or on Open Racks.
[src:authoritative-server/server-computing] These types of servers are often housed in dedicated data centers.
[src:authoritative-server/server-computing] These will normally have very stable power and Internet and increased security.
[src:authoritative-server/server-computing] Noise is also less of a concern, but power consumption and heat output can be a serious issue.
[src:authoritative-server/server-computing] Server rooms are equipped with air conditioning devices.
[src:authoritative-server/server-computing] A *server farm* or *server cluster* is a collection of computer servers maintained by an organization to supply server functionality far beyond the capability of a single device.
[src:authoritative-server/server-computing] Modern data centers are now often built of very large clusters of much simpler servers, and there is a collaborative effort, Open Compute Project around this concept.
[src:authoritative-server/server-computing] A class of small specialist servers called network appliances are generally at the low end of the scale, often being smaller than common desktop computers.
[src:authoritative-server/server-computing] A mobile server has a portable form factor, e.g. a laptop.
[src:authoritative-server/server-computing] In contrast to large data centers or rack servers, the mobile server is designed for on-the-road or *ad hoc* deployment into emergency, disaster or temporary environments where traditional servers are not feasible due to their power requirements, size, and deployment time.
[src:authoritative-server/server-computing] The main beneficiaries of so-called "server on the go" technology include network managers, software or database developers, training centers, military personnel, law enforcement, forensics, emergency relief groups, and service organizations.
[src:authoritative-server/server-computing] To facilitate portability, features such as the keyboard, display, battery (uninterruptible power supply, to provide power redundancy in case of failure), and mouse are all integrated into the chassis.
[src:authoritative-server/server-computing] On the Internet, the dominant operating systems among servers are UNIX-like open-source distributions, such as those based on Linux and FreeBSD, with Windows Server also having a significant share.
[src:authoritative-server/server-computing] Proprietary operating systems such as z/OS and macOS Server are also deployed, but in much smaller numbers.
[src:authoritative-server/server-computing] Servers that run Linux are commonly used as Webservers or Databanks.
[src:authoritative-server/server-computing] Windows Servers are used for Networks that are made out of Windows Clients.
[src:authoritative-server/server-computing] In practice, today many desktop and server operating systems share similar code bases, differing mostly in configuration.
[src:authoritative-server/server-computing] In 2024, data centers (servers, cooling, and other electrical infrastructure) consumed 415 terawatt-hours of electrical energy, and were responsible for roughly 1.5% of electrical energy consumption worldwide, and for 4.4% in the United States.
[src:authoritative-server/server-computing] One estimate is that total energy consumption for information and communications technology saves more than 5 times its carbon footprint in the rest of the economy by increasing efficiency.
[src:authoritative-server/server-computing] Concerns about data centers' environmental impact focus on their electricity demand and associated emissions, especially as AI workloads increase server and cooling requirements.
